FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART III
ExplntnTxt: THUNDERBIRD SCHOOL OF GLOBAL MANAGEMENT EIN: 86-0105586 ON APRIL 8, 1946, THUNDERBIRD SCHOOL OF GLOBAL MANAGEMENT (THUNDERBIRD) (ORIGINALLY KNOWN AS THE AMERICAN INSTITUTE FOR FOREIGN TRADE [AIFT]) WAS CHARTERED ON THE GLENDALE, ARIZONA WORLD WAR II AIRBASE, THUNDERBIRD FIELD, WHERE PILOTS FROM AROUND THE WORLD CAME FOR TRAINING DURING WARTIME. GENERAL BARTON KYLE YOUNT OBTAINED THE AIRFIELD WITH THE EXPRESS PURPOSE OF DEVELOPING A SCHOOL FOCUSED EXCLUSIVELY ON INTERNATIONAL TRADE AND GLOBAL RELATIONS. AS AIFT, THUNDERBIRD BECAME THE FIRST-EVER HIGHER-EDUCATION INSTITUTION TO FOCUS EXCLUSIVELY ON INTERNATIONAL MANAGEMENT BY CONCENTRATING CURRICULUM ON CROSS-CULTURAL COMMUNICATION, REGIONAL BUSINESS STUDIES, AND HANDS-ON, REAL-WORLD TRAINING IN GLOBAL BUSINESS NUANCES. BY 1955, THERE WERE TWO DEGREES OFFERED: A BACHELOR OF FOREIGN TRADE AND A MASTER OF FOREIGN TRADE. OVER THE YEARS, THE BACHELOR'S PROGRAM WAS DISCONTINUED AND THE MASTER'S PROGRAM MORPHED INTO A MASTER OF INTERNATIONAL MANAGEMENT (MIM). IN 2001, THE MIM WAS ADAPTED INTO AN MBA IN GLOBAL MANAGEMENT TO RESPOND TO THE GROWING DEMAND FOR GRADUATES WITH A BUSINESS ADMINISTRATION FOCUS. DURING THOSE SAME YEARS, THUNDERBIRD EXPANDED ITS DEGREE PROGRAM OFFERINGS TO INCLUDE AN ONLINE MBA, AN EXECUTIVE MBA, AND EARLY-CAREER MASTER'S DEGREES LIKE THE MASTER OF ARTS IN GLOBAL AFFAIRS & MANAGEMENT. THE SCHOOL CONSISTENTLY RANKED #1 FOR INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS FOR MANY YEARS, SETTING THE STANDARD FOR GLOBAL MANAGEMENT EDUCATION WORLDWIDE. AT THE SAME TIME, THUNDERBIRD EXECUTIVE EDUCATION OFFERED OPEN PROGRAMS FOR INDIVIDUALS SEEKING CAREER DEVELOPMENT OPPORTUNITIES AND CUSTOM PROGRAMS FOR GLOBAL ORGANIZATIONS LOOKING FOR INDIVIDUALIZED DEVELOPMENT SOLUTIONS FOR THEIR UNIQUE CHALLENGES. RANKED AMONG THE WORLD'S BEST EXECUTIVE EDUCATION PROGRAMS, THUNDERBIRD'S EDUCATIONAL OFFERINGS EXPANDED OVER THE YEARS TO INCLUDE A ROBUST SELECTION OF ONLINE EXECUTIVE CERTIFICATE PROGRAMS, INTERNATIONAL CONSORTIA PROGRAMS, EXECUTIVE COACHING, AND MORE. IN DECEMBER OF 2014, THUNDERBIRD ENTERED INTO AN AGREEMENT WITH ARIZONA STATE UNIVERSITY (ASU) TO INTEGRATE THUNDERBIRD INTO THE GREATER ASU KNOWLEDGE ENTERPRISE IN ORDER TO CREATE MORE IN DEPTH AND BROADER REACHING EDUCATION TO STUDENTS AND EXECUTIVES INTERNATIONALLY. AS PART OF THIS AGREEMENT, ALL US EMPLOYEES AND DEGREE SEEKING STUDENTS OF THUNDERBIRD BECAME EMPLOYEES AND STUDENTS OF ASU. THUNDERBIRD'S EXECUTIVE EDUCATION PROGRAM, CERTAIN INTERNATIONAL PROGRAMS, AND MOST THUNDERBIRD ASSETS REMAINED WITH THUNDERBIRD. THE PROGRAMS AND SERVICES THAT REMAIN WITH THUNDERBIRD CONTINUE TO FURTHER THUNDERBIRD'S CHARITABLE AND EDUCATIONAL PURPOSES, INCLUDING BY SUPPORTING ASU. BEGINNING IN FISCAL YEAR 2015, AND IN ORDER TO MORE ACCURATELY REFLECT THE CURRENT CHARITABLE AND EDUCATIONAL ACTIVITIES OF THUNDERBIRD, THUNDERBIRD BELIEVES IT NOW IS APPROPRIATE TO REPORT AS A PUBLICLY SUPPORTED PUBLIC CHARITY UNDER SECTION 509(A)(2) OF THE CODE. IN CONJUNCTION WITH THIS DECISION AND TRANSITION, THUNDERBIRD IS ENGAGING IN INTERNAL EFFORTS TO IDENTIFY AND DEVELOP NEW SOURCES OF PUBLIC SUPPORT RELATIVE TO THUNDERBIRD'S CURRENT PROGRAMS AND SERVICES. AS A SCHOOL DESCRIBED IN SECTION 170(B)(1)(A)(II) OF THE CODE, THUNDERBIRD WAS NOT REQUIRED TO CONSIDER WHICH OF ITS REVENUES REPORTED ON LINES 1, 2, OR 3 OF PART III OF SCHEDULE A WERE RECEIVED FROM DISQUALIFIED PERSONS AND DOES NOT HAVE RECORDS SUFFICIENT TO MAKE THIS DETERMINATION. ACCORDINGLY, IN ORDER TO COMPLETE PART III OF SCHEDULE A, THUNDERBIRD HAS ASSUMED, FOR PURPOSES OF CALCULATING ITS PUBLIC SUPPORT PERCENTAGE, THAT ALL GIFTS, GRANTS, CONTRIBUTIONS, AND MEMBERSHIP FEES REPORTED ON LINE 1 WERE RECEIVED FROM DISQUALIFIED PERSONS, EXCEPT TO THE EXTENT THAT THUNDERBIRD'S RECORDS CLEARLY INDICATE AMOUNTS OF SUPPORT RECEIVED FROM GOVERNMENTAL UNITS OR ORGANIZATIONS DESCRIBED IN SECTION 509(A)(1) OF THE CODE. BEGINNING IN TAX YEAR 2014 ALL AMOUNTS ARE TRACKED AND REPORTED THEREFORE, BEGINNING IN FY19 AN ACCURATE REFLECTION OF DISQUALFIED DONORS IS INCLUDED ON THE SCHEDULE. FOR FY19 THERE WERE NO DISQUALIFED DONORS. IN 2018 THUNDERBIRD WAS APPROACHED BY ARIZONA CHRISTIAN UNIVERSITY (ACU) ABOUT EXCHANGING THE THUNDERBIRD GLENDALE CAMPUS WITH ACU'S NORTH PHOENIX CAMPUS. THIS EXCHANGE MET THE NEEDS OF THUNDERBIRD IN THEIR FUTURE STRATEGIC AND PROGRAMMATIC PLANS PROJECTIONS AND THIS EXCHANGE WAS FINALIZED NOVEMBER 2018. THIS RESULTED IN A CAPITAL ASSET WRITE OFF OF JUST OVER $9 MILLION DOLLARS. AS THIS CAPITAL ASSET WRITE OFF WAS DUE TO THE EXCHANGE OF CAPITAL ASSETS, IT IS NOT REQUIRED TO BE COUNTED IN THE CALCUATION OF PUBLIC SUPPORT. IN 2019 THE ACU CAMPUS WAS SOLD TO AN UNRELATED THIRD PARTY WHICH RESULTED IN A CAPITAL GAIN OF JUST OVER $4 MILLION DOLLARS. AS THE GAIN WAS RELATED TO THE SALE OF CAPITAL ASSETS, THE GAIN IS NOT REQUIRED TO BE COUNTED IN THE CALCUATION OF PUBLIC SUPPORT. ALSO, IN 2019 THUNDERBIRD WAS THE RECIPIENT OF A $4 MILLION DOLLAR BEQUEST FROM AN ALUM, THIS CONTRIBUTION MEETS THE DEFINITION OF AN UNUSUAL GRANT UNDER 1.509(A)-3(C)(3) AND HAS BEEN EXCLUDED FROM THE PUBLIC SUPPORT TEST.

ExplntnTxt: Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute ("Rensselaer") is a school described in Section 170(b)(1(A)(ii) and checked box 2 on Schedul A, Part I on the current year and previously filed Form 990 returns. Instructions for Form 990, Part IV, line 2 requires an organization to answer "Yes" if it meets the 33 1/3% support test of the requlations under sections 509(a)(1) and 170(b)(1)(A)(vi), checks the box on Schedule A, Part II, line 13, 16a or 16b and received from any one contributor contributions of the greater of $5,000 or 2% of the amount on Part VIII, line 1h. Rensselaer meets this test and have answered "Yes" to Part IV, line 2 which requires completing Schedule B. Furthermore, the instructions states that an organization filing Schedule B can limit the contributors it reports on Schedule B to greater than 2% of the amount on Part VIII, line 1h only if it checks the box on Schedule A, Part II, line 13, 16a or 16b. However, the tax software that Rensslaer uses to prepare the Form 990 will not display Schedule A, Part II when box 2 is checked on Schedule A, Part I. To be compliant with the instructions for Form 990, Part IV, line 2, Rensselaer is submitting the completed Scheduel A, Part II as a separate attachment.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: Schedule A, Part II, Line 17a 10% FACTS & CIRCUMSTANCES TEST - 2019
ExplntnTxt: TREAS. REGS. SECTION 1.170A-9(F)(3)(I) PROVIDES THAT IN ORDER TO MEET THE "FACTS AND CIRCUMSTANCES" TEST, THE ORGANIZATION MUST NORMALLY RECEIVE SUBSTANTIAL SUPPORT (MORE THAN 10%) FROM CONTRIBUTIONS FROM GOVERNMENTAL UNITS, THE GENERAL PUBLIC, OR A COMBINATION OF THESE SOURCES. COMPLETE COLLEGE HAS RECEIVED APPROXIMATELY 22.72% IN PUBLIC SUPPORT, SUBSTANTIALLY ABOVE THE 10% THRESHOLD. IN ADDITION TO THE 10% THRESHOLD TEST, TREAS. REGS. SECTION 1.170A-9(F)(3)(II) PROVIDES THAT THE ORGANIZATION MUST BE ORGANIZED AND OPERATED SO AS TO ATTRACT NEW AND ADDITIONAL PUBLIC OR GOVERNMENTAL SUPPORT ON A CONTINUOUS BASIS. AN ORGANIZATION WILL MEET THIS REQUIREMENT IF IT: -MAINTAINS A CONTINUOUS AND BONA FIDE PROGRAM FOR THE SOLICITATION OF FUNDS FROM THE GENERAL PUBLIC, OR -IT CARRIES ON ACTIVITIES DESIGNED TO ATTRACT SUPPORT FROM THE GOVERNMENT OR 509(A)(1) CHARITIES. COMPLETE COLLEGE SATISFIES BOTH TESTS. IT MAINTAINS A CONTINUOUS AND BONA FIDE PROGRAM FOR CHARITABLE CONTRIBUTIONS FROM THE PUBLIC AND CARRIES ON THE TYPE OF CHARITABLE ACTIVITIES THAT ARE DESIGNED TO ATTRACT SUPPORT FROM GOVERNMENTAL UNITS AND THE GENERAL PUBLIC AS IS EVIDENCED BY THE SIGNIFICANT STATE GOVERNMENT INVOLVEMENT WITH COMPLETE COLLEGE IN ITS "COMPLETION PROGRAM".

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2A:
ExplntnTxt: THE CLUB AT THE UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, SAN DIEGO (UCSD) IS PHYSICALLY LOCATED ON THE UCSD CAMPUS WITH A LONG-TERM LEASE FROM UCSD. THE CLUB WAS FOUNDED IN 1988 TO PROVIDE A PLACE IN A CENTRAL LOCATION FOR COLLEAGUES AND COMMUNITY TO SOCIALIZE AND INTELLECTUALIZE OVER FOOD IN A CASUAL ATMOSPHERE OF UCSD. MEMBERSHIP IN THE CLUB IS REQUIRED FOR PARTICIPATION AND IS LIMITED TO FACULTY, STAFF AND GRADUATE STUDENTS AS WELL AS RETIRED EMPLOYEES, COMMUNITY MEMBERS WITH AN INTEREST IN THE EDUCATIONAL AND INTELLECTUAL LIFE OF THE CAMPUS, PERSONS AT OTHER SELECT NON-PROFIT RESEARCH INSTITUTIONS, CHANCELLORS ASSOCIATES AND SELECT BUSINESSES ADDING TO THE EDUCATIONAL AND INTELLECTUAL LIFE OF THE CAMPUS (MUST BE APPROVED BY 2/3 VOTE OF THE BOARD), AND CAMPUS DEPARTMENTS. LUNCHEON MEALS ARE SERVED WEEKDAYS AND PERIODIC SPECIAL EVENTS ARE SCHEDULED.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2B:
ExplntnTxt: WITHOUT THE CLUB, NO SINGLE SPACE OF SUFFICIENT SIZE WOULD BE AVAILABLE REGULARLY NOR MEALS SERVED. THE CASUAL ATMOSPHERE AND CENTRAL LOCATION OF THE CLUB SERVES AS A FOCAL POINT FOR UCSD EMPLOYEES AND SUPPORTERS. IT ALLOWS FORMAL AND INFORMAL GATHERINGS OF UCSD COLLEAGUES AND A MEETING PLACE FOR ACTIVITIES. SOME OF THESE ACTIVITIES WOULD CONTINUE ON AN AD HOC BASIS IN THE ABSENCE OF THE CLUB, BUT THE CLUB WAS ESTABLISHED TO FACILITATE THESE INTERACTIONS.

ExplntnTxt: THE SUPPORTED ORGANIZATION IS KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY (KSU). FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2B
ExplntnTxt: TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER IS CLOSELY LINKED TO FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH ACTIVITIES IN UNIVERSITIES. UNDER THE BAYH-DOLE ACT OF 1980, UNIVERSITIES HAVE THE ABILITY TO RETAIN TITLE TO AND PROMOTE THE COMMERCIALIZATION OF INVENTIONS DEVELOPED UNDER GOVERNMENT FUNDING. WITH THIS ELECTION, UNIVERSITIES ARE REQUIRED TO PROPERLY MANAGE THE INVENTIONS INCLUDING REPORTING REQUIREMENTS, FILING PATENTS, MARKETING AND LICENSING THE INVENTION AND DISTRIBUTING RETURNS. THE REQUIREMENTS NECESSARY TO ADHERE TO THE BAYH-DOLE ACT ARE CONTRACTED TO KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY RESEARCH FOUNDATION BY KSU. IF THE KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY RESEARCH FOUNDATION DID NOT EXIST, KSU WOULD STILL BE REQUIRED TO CONFORM TO THESE REQUIREMENTS.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART 1 - REASON FOR PUBLIC CHARITY STATUS
ExplntnTxt: THE COLLEGE IS CLASSIFIED AS A PUBLIC CHARITY, A SCHOOL, IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 170(B)(1)(A)(II) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE. HOWEVER, THE COLLEGE HAS ELECTED TO FOLLOW THE "SPECIAL RULE" FOR REPORTING CONTRIBUTIONS ON SCHEDULE B WHICH PROVIDES THAT 501(C)(3) ORGANIZATIONS THAT SATISFY THE 33 1/3% SUPPORT TESTS OF SECTIONS 509(A)(1) AND 170(B)(1)(A)(VI) NEED ONLY DISCLOSE ON SCHEDULE B GIFTS FROM ANY ONE CONTRIBUTOR THAT TOTAL THE GREATER OF (1) $5,000 OR (2) 2% OF TOTAL CONTRIBUTIONS, GIFTS, GRANTS AND SIMILAR AMOUNTS RECEIVED. FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION D, LINE 3:
ExplntnTxt: THE LSU SCHOOL OF MEDICINE IN NEW ORLEANS FACULTY GROUP PRACTICE (LSUHN) IS A SUPPORTING ORGANIZATION OF LSU HEALTH SCIENCES CENTER - NEW ORLEANS (LSUHSC). LSUHN'S FINANCE AND EXECUTIVE COMMITTEES ARE CONTROLLED BY LSUHSC AND THIS ENABLES LSUHSC TO HAVE A SIGNIFICANT VOICE IN THE OPERATIONS OF LSUHN. LSUHN IS CONSIDERED A BLENDED COMPONENT UNIT OF THE UNIVERSITY SYSTEM AND IS INCLUDED IN THE LOUISIANA STATE UNIVERSITY SYSTEM FINANCIAL STATEMENTS. THE COMPONENT UNIT IS INCLUDED IN THE REPORTING ENTITY BECAUSE OF THE SIGNIFICANCE OF ITS OPERATIONAL AND FINANCIAL RELATIONSHIPS WITH THE LSU SYSTEM AND THE LSUHSC. THIS BLENDING PROVIDES THE LSU SYSTEM AND LSUHSC WITH FULL KNOWLEDGE OF THE FINANCIAL MATTERS OF LSUHN.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: SCHEDULE A, PART IV, SECTION A, LINE 6
ExplntnTxt: THE MISSION OF THE RESEARCH FOUNDATION IS TO SUPPORT OUR MEMBERS IN IMPROVING THE HEALTH OF ALL SOUTH CAROLINIANS BY COLLABORATING ACROSS THE STATE OF SOUTH CAROLINA, REGIONALLY, AND NATIONALLY. GRANT FUNDS WERE PROVIDED TO NON-SUPPORTED ORGANIZATIONS PARTICIPATING IN THE SOUTH CAROLINA SURGICAL QUALITY COLLABORATIVE (SCSQC) AND CAROLINAS COLLABORATIVE. THE RESEARCH FOUNDATION WAS AWARDED FUNDING FROM AN EXTERNAL SOURCE FOR THE SCSQC TO IMPROVE SURGICAL QUALITY SAFETY IN THE STATE. THE COLLABORATIVE HAS PARTNERED WITH SURGICAL LEADERS AT HOSPITALS (SUPPORTED ORGANIZATIONS AND NON-SUPPORTED ORGANIZATIONS) ACROSS THE STATE TO ESTABLISH A CONTINUOUS QUALITY IMPROVEMENT STRUCTURE AND LEARNING HEALTHCARE SYSTEM. EACH PARTICIPATING HOSPITAL RECEIVED FUNDS DURING THE GRANT PERIOD FOR KEY PERSONNEL ALLOCATED TO THE EFFORTS OF THE COLLABORATIVE. THE RESEARCH FOUNDATION WAS AWARDED FUNDING FROM AN EXTERNAL SOURCE FOR THE CAROLINAS COLLABORATIVE FOR THE PURPOSE OF UNITING HEALTHCARE INSTITUTIONS, UNIVERSITIES AND COMMUNITITES ACROSS NORTH CAROLINA AND SOUTH CAROLINA TO ENHANCE THE QUALITY OF HEALTHCARE AND ACCELERATE ADVANCES IN RESEARCH. THE PARTICIPATING INSTITUTIONS RECEIVED FUNDS DURING THE GRANT PERIOD FOR KEY PERSONNEL ALLOCATED TO INFRASTRUCTURE DEVELOPMENT AND RESEARCH INITIATIVES.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: SCHEDULE A, PART IV, SECTION D, LINE 3
ExplntnTxt: NO INVESTMENTS ARE HELD BY THE ORGANIZATION. A PORTION OF THE ORGANIZATION'S BUDGET SUPPORTS THE ACTIVITIES OF THE SUPPORTED ORGANIZATIONS, AND TO THE EXTENT THAT EXPENDITURES NEEDED TO BE REVISED OR INCREASED TO MAINTAIN THAT SUPPORT, SUCH CHANGES WERE MADE TO THE EXPENDITURES.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: SCHEDULE A, PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2A
ExplntnTxt: EXCLUDING THE SPECIFIC WORK IN SCIMPH AND HSSC, SUBSTANTIALLY ALL OF THE ACTIVITY IN THE SCRF PERTAINED TO SUPPORTING THE UNIVERSITY OF SOUTH CAROLINA RESEARCH MISSION. ALL OF SCRF PROGRAM SERVICES (SPONSORED AWARDS TO SCRF MANAGED AND CONTROLLED BY USC, $6 MILLION) AND 100% OF ITS MANAGEMENT AND GENERAL EXPENSES ($648K) WERE SPECIFIC TO USC SPONSORED PROGRAMS AND TO SUPPORT RESEARCH PERSONNEL AND ACTIVITIES AT USC. THIS CONSTITUTES 99% OF THE SCRF EXPENDITURES AND REVENUE.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: SCHEDULE A, PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2B
ExplntnTxt: ONE OF THE PRIMARY MISSIONS OF ANY LARGE STATE RESEARCH UNIVERSITY IS TO ENGAGE IN RESEARCH. USC ENGAGES IN RESEARCH DIRECTLY WITH EXTERNAL SPONSORS AND WITH THE SUPPORT OF SCRF. IN SOME CASES, SPONSORS PREFER THE ORGANIZATIONAL FORMATION OF SCRF AND SCRF IS ABLE TO ACCOMMODATE THEM TO THE BENEFIT OF THE EXTERNAL SPONSOR AND USC.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: SCHEDULE A, PART I
ExplntnTxt: THE UNIVERSITY IS CLASSIFIED AS A PUBLIC CHARITY, A SCHOOL, IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 170(B)(1)(A)(II) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE. HOWEVER, THE UNIVERSITY HAS ELECTED TO FOLLOW THE "SPECIAL RULE" FOR REPORTING CONTRIBUTIONS ON SCHEDULE B WHICH PROVIDES THAT 501(C)(3) ORGANIZATIONS THAT SATISFY THE 33 1/3% SUPPORT TESTS OF SECTIONS 509(A)(1) AND 170(B)(1)(A)(VI) NEED ONLY DISCLOSE ON SCHEDULE B GIFTS FROM ANY ONE CONTRIBUTOR THAT TOTAL THE GREATER OF (1) $5,000 OR (2) 2% OF TOTAL CONTRIBUTIONS, GIFTS, GRANTS AND SIMILAR AMOUNTS RECEIVED. THEREFORE, THE UNIVERSITY HAS CHECKED SCHEDULE A, PART I, BOX 2 AND COMPLETED THE SUPPORT SCHEDULE IN PART II TO SUBSTANTIATE THAT IT MEETS THE PUBLIC SUPPORT TEST.
